%S A369254 1,2,3,5,7,11,12,13,16,17,18,19,20,23,28,29,31,32,36,37,41,43,44,45,
%T A369254 47,48,50,52,53,59,61,63,67,68,71,73,75,76,79,80,81,83,89,92,97,98,99,
%U A369254 100,101,103,107,109,112,113,116,117,124,127,131,137,139,147,148,149,151,153,157,162,163,164,167,171,172,173
%N A369254 Numbers k that have an odd number of divisors that are at most sqrt(k).
%C A369254 k is a term iff its prime signature either has exactly one term == 1 (mod 4) with all other terms even, or all terms even with an even number of terms == 2 (mod 4). - _Robert Israel_, Mar 05 2026
%H A369254 Robert Israel, <a href="/A369254/b369254.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A369254 1 has just one divisor 1, which is <= sqrt(1), therefore 1 is included.
%e A369254 Of the two divisors of 2, [1, 2], only 1 is at most sqrt(2), therefore 2 is included.
%e A369254 Of the three divisors of 4, [1, 2, 4], the first two are <= sqrt(4), and as two is not an odd number, 4 is NOT included in this sequence.
%p A369254 filter:= proc(n) local F;
%p A369254   F:= ifactors(n)[2][..,2] mod 4;
%p A369254   if hastype(F,odd) then numboccur(1,F) = 1 and not member(3,F)
%p A369254   else numboccur(2,F)::even
%p A369254   fi
%p A369254 end proc:
%p A369254 select(filter, [$1..1000]); # _Robert Israel_, Mar 05 2026
%o A369254 (PARI) \\ See A369253.
